International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

In this posting:
[1] Switzerland (Appenzell Outer Rhodes)
[2] Liechtenstein: suspected

******
[1] Switzerland (Appenzell Outer Rhodes)
Date: Thu 26 Sep 2013
Source: Appenzell Outer Rhodes official cantonal website, news release [in German, trans. submitter SZ, edited]
http://tinyurl.com/l3azdtq


On 11 Sep 2013, a slaughtered cow from Appenzell Outer Rhodes was diagnosed with tuberculosis at post mortem inspection. The official veterinarian immediately put restrictions on the farm of origin. Meanwhile it was confirmed that the animal tested positive for _Mycobacterium caprae_. Skin tests [tuberculin] on the farm gave positive results on more animals, which will be slaughtered.

A total of 10 animals tested positive and have been slaughtered already. Organ samples will be tested for the bacterium. A further 10 animals gave an inconclusive result and will be slaughtered as well to prevent transmission of disease. The remainder of the herd tested negative. There is no connection with recent confirmation of [bovine tuberculosis] bTB in the West of Switzerland.

Further investigations will look into the possibility that the animal might have become infected with "deer tuberculosis" during the summer of 2011 when it had been put out to grazing (transhumance) in Vorarlberg (Austria).

A search for contact farms is ongoing and investigations are underway to identify the origin of the infection.

The farm is under restrictions, which will only be lifted after 2 clear [negative] tuberculin tests are obtained. So far no other farms in the region are affected.

Humans can become infected when drinking raw [unpasteurised] milk or through contact with an infected animal but the risk is low. Milk from the affected holding has not been processed for food.

