<CVLonghorns@aol.com>

[A HealthMap/ProMED-mail interactive map of Liechtenstein can be seen at http://healthmap.org/r/4wFb. - Sr.Tech.Ed.MJ]

Switzerland obtained its status as a country officially free of bovine tuberculosis in 1960. Since 1980, the control of bovine tuberculosis (bTB) has been reduced to passive abattoir surveillance, in line with OIE's requirements as specified in chapter 11.6 of OIE's Terrestrial Animal Health Code (http://www.oie.int/index.php?id=169&L=0&htmfile=chapitre_1.11.6.htm).

Isolated cases of bTB, partly due to reactivation of human _Mycobacterium bovis_ infections with subsequent transmission to cattle, have been noticed in Switzerland over the years. After the absence of bTB since 2000, 2 outbreaks, caused by _M. bovis_ spp. _bovis_ (_M. bovis_), were reported in March 2013 from west Switzerland: the 1st one related to a single dairy cow in the canton Fribourg; the 2nd one related to a single dairy cow in neighbouring canton Vaud, which originated from the index farm in Fribourg and therefore was not regarded a spread of the infection. The current case, on the opposite (eastern) side of the country, has been caused by _M. bovis_ spp. _caprae_ (_M. caprae_).

According to information published by Switzerland's Federal Veterinary Office (FVO), to investigate the possibility that the animal might have become infected with _M. caprae_ during the summer of 2011 while grazing in Vorarlberg (Austria), systematic sampling of other cows, which were grazing in the Vorarlberg Alps during the same period, has been undertaken. This relates to around 104 live animals spread over 27 farms in 5 eastern Swiss cantons and in the Principality of Liechtenstein.

No bTB cases have been reported from Liechtenstein to the OIE, at least since 2002; the last year of occurrence is not known. Austria reported, during 2012, 3 outbreaks in Tyrol. During January-June 2013, 2 outbreaks were reported from Tyrol and 2 from Vorarlberg. Germany reported 6 outbreaks during 2012; locations not given. No report is yet available for January-June 2013.

Bovine tuberculosis (bTB) is caused primarily by _Mycobacterium bovis_ spp. _bovis_ (_M. bovis_) and, to a lesser extent, by _Mycobacterium bovis_ spp. _caprae_ (_M. caprae_).

According to chapter 2.4.7 ("Bovine tuberculosis") of OIE's Manual of Diagnostic Tests and Vaccines for Terrestrial Animals 2012, "Disease caused by _M. caprae_ is not considered to be substantially different from that caused by _M. bovis_ and the same tests can be used for its diagnosis. In countries with tuberculosis eradication programmes, clinical evidence of tuberculosis in cattle is seldom encountered because the intradermal tuberculin test enables presumptive diagnosis and elimination of infected animals before signs appear."

Switzerland, similarly to its mentioned neighbouring countries, maintains its status as "officially bTB free", since "_M. bovis_ infection was not present in at least 99.8 per cent of the herds and 99.9 per cent of the cattle for 5 consecutive years". Switzerland's cattle population (OIE 2012 data) is 1 570 344 head in 41 000 establishments.

Further reading
---------------
1. Prodinger WM, Eigentler A, Allerberger F, et al: Infection of red deer, cattle, and humans with _Mycobacterium bovis_ subsp. _caprae_ in Western Austria. J Clin Microbiol. 2002; 40(6): 2270-2. Available at http://jcm.asm.org/content/40/6/2270.long.
2. Kubica T, Ruesch-Gerdes S, Niemann S: _Mycobacterium bovis_ subsp. _caprae_ caused one-third of human _M. bovis_-associated tuberculosis cases reported in Germany between 1999 and 2001. J Clin Microbiol. 2003 Jul; 41(7): 3070-7. Available at http://jcm.asm.org/content/41/7/3070.long. - Mod.AS]
